Avoid breaking `process.env`'s coercing to string behavior.

The prior version of this test cleanup assigned `process.env` to a
simple javascript object (`{}`), which **does** properly reset the
values of `process.env` (which was the goal of the cleanup).

Unfortunately, assining `process.env` to any _other_ value breaks the
built-in string coercion that happens whenever you assing something to
`process.env`.

Consider this test script:

```js
const assert = require('assert');

process.env.FOO = true;
assert.equal(process.env.FOO, 'true');

process.env.FOO = false;
assert.equal(process.env.FOO, 'false');

process.env.FOO = undefined;
assert.equal(process.env.FOO, 'undefined');

process.env.FOO = 1;
assert.equal(process.env.FOO, '1');

// now clobber process.env, and test again
process.env = {};

process.env.FOO = true;
assert.equal(process.env.FOO, 'true');

process.env.FOO = false;
assert.equal(process.env.FOO, 'false');

process.env.FOO = undefined;
assert.equal(process.env.FOO, 'undefined');

process.env.FOO = 1;
assert.equal(process.env.FOO, '1');
```

:mind_blown:

Turn experiments object into a function

When testing an experiment in `ember-cli` scope, a new CI scenario seems
to be the go-to solution. This involves scopping tests like this:
```js
if (experiments.MY_EXPERIMENT) {
  describe('my experiment module', ...)
  // or
  module('my experiment module', ...)
} else {
  describe('regular module', ...)
  // or
  module('regular module', ...)
}
```

But when testing an experiment outside of `ember-cli` scope, things get
different. And we may want to be able to do:

```js
describe('my addon blueprint', {
  it('works - in a classic app', ...);

  it('works - in a MU app', ...);
})
```

The issue is: as an object, `experiments` is cached between the two
tests (run on the same process). In these scenarios, we need not to
cache the object, hence the function.

Config hook called too soon during serve

The config hook gets called eagerly during the serve flow and that
leads to issues with the context of the config hooks not being set
up properly. An example of this is if you have:

config() {
  return this.app && this.app.options[this.name];
}

`this.app` will be undefined but that same hook during a build will
not be undefined.

Migrate to new format for mode specific arguments.

Testem is deprecating the format currently in use:

```js
browser_args: {
  Chrome: {
    mode: 'ci',
    args: [
      // args go here....
    ]
  }
}
```

In favor of this format:

```js
browser_args: {
  Chrome: {
    ci: [
      // args go here....
    ]
  }
}
```

This change is being made so that Testem can support using different
sets of arguments for different modes. The change also adds an `all` key
that can be used for shared arguments between modes (they are merged
with the mode specific args).

Restore `separator: '\n;'` to vendor JS concat

Prior to 2.17, Ember CLI used a semicolon to separate files concatenated into vendor.js: https://github.com/ember-cli/ember-cli/blob/v2.16.2/lib/broccoli/bundler.js#L92

Vendor shims are still generated with a leading paren:
```
(function() {
  function vendorModule() {
    'use strict';

    return {
      'default': self['test'],
      __esModule: true,
    };
  }

  define('test', [], vendorModule);
})();
```

This can cause `TypeError: (intermediate value)(...) is not a function` if the code immediately prior does not end in a semicolon.
.

Add Replacer to FileInfo

This enables a blueprint to augment the output of a given file provided.

A concrete example would be a package.json replacer.

```js
function replacer(content) {
  let pkg = JSON.parse(content);

  delete pkg.devDependencies['ember-resolver'];
  delete pkg.devDependencies['ember-ajax'];

  pkg.devDependencies['ember-strict-resolver'] = '^0.0.3';
  pkg.devDependencies['ember-native-dom-helpers'] = '^0.4.1';
  pkg.devDependencies['ember-native-dom-event-dispatcher'] = '^0.6.1';
  pkg.devDependencies['ember-fetch'] = '^2.1.0';

  return JSON.stringify(pkg, null, 2);
}


let options = { 
  /* other valid options */,
  replacer
};

let info = new FileInfo(options);
```

