## Overview

paired with @stefanpenner

Improved analytics output, largely spike on missing infrastructure to make #6349
possible.

The intent is to provide a private API endpoint with a reasonable API, iterate,
and then see if we want to make this public.

## API

The single entry point will be an initially private api hook,
`_buildInstrumentation`, inside an addon's main entry file (typically
`index.js`).

This hook is invoked if the environment variable `EMBER_CLI_INSTRUMENTATION` is
set.

The hook is passed an analytics object that has two properties:

  1. `summary` - A POJO containing build information and
  2. `buildTree` A tree representation of the build pipeline, with a tree and
     stats iteration api.

### Hook

The hook is invoked if the environment variable `EMBER_CLI_INSTRUMENTATION` is
set.

```js
// index.js
module.exports = {
  // _ to indicate this hook is private and potentially unstable for now
  _buildInstrumentation(instrumentation) {
  }
}
```

### instrumentation argument

```js
{
  summary: /* described below */
  buildTree: /* described below */
}
```

#### Summary

The summary POJO has the following shape:

```js
{
  summary: {
    build: {
      type,
      count,
      outputChangedFiles,

      primaryFile,
      changedFileCount,
      changedFiles,
    },
    output,
    totalTime,
    buildSteps,
  }
}
```

The properties are as follows:

- `summary.build.type` one of `'initial'` or `'rebuild'`
- `summary.build.count` the number of the build (0 for initial build, > 0 for
  rebuilds).
- `summary.build.outputChangedFiles` an array of paths to output files that
  changed during this build.  These paths are relative to the `dist` directory.
- `summary.build.primaryFile` only present for rebuilds.  Indicates the first
  file the watcher noticed had changed.
- `summary.build.changedFileCount` only present for rebuilds.  The number of
  files the watcher had noticed changed before the build started.
- `summary.build.changedFiles` only present for rebuilds. The first 10 files
  the watcher had noticed changed before the build started.
- `summary.output` The temp directory containing the results of the build.
- `summary.totalTime`
- `summary.buildSteps` The number of build steps (broccoli nodes) in the build tree.

#### buildTree

The broccoli build pipeline can be thought of as a tree of broccoli nodes, as
well as more fine grained nodes (such as `applyPatches` and `computePatches`,
referring to fs-tree-diff patches).  The `buildTree` object represents the root
of this tree and provides APIs for iterating the tree and iterating stats

#### API

- `node.label`

Description: a POJO property that describes the node.  It will always include a `name`
property, and for broccoli nodes will also include a `broccoliNode` property.
Example:

```js
node.label == {
  name: 'TreeMerger (allTrees)',
  broccoliNode: true,
}
```

- `node.toJSON`

Description: Returns a POJO that represents the serialized tree.  This POJO will
have a single key, `nodes`, an array of POJOs with the following properties:
- `id` an arbitrary node identifier.
- `children` an array of node identifiers for the children of this node
- `label` a POJO that describes this node.  Exactly as `node.label`.
- `stats` a POJO that describes the stats collected for this node.  It will
  include:
  - `time.self` - The time spent within this node (not including its
    descendants) in nanoseconds.
  - `fs` a POJO that includes the counts of all invocations of methods in
    `fs`, as well as the cumulative times spent in each method.
  - `own` any custom stats specific to this node.

Example:

  ```js
  // for a tree
  //  TreeMerger
  //    |- Babel_1
  //    |- Babel_2
  //    |--|- Funnel
  console.log(JSON.stringify(node.toJSON(), null, 2));
  // might print
  //
  {
    nodes: [{
      id: 1,
      children: [2,3],
      stats: {
        time: {
          self: 5000000,
        },
        fs: {
          lstat: {
            count: 2,
            time: 2000000
          }
        },
        own: {
        }
      }
    }, {
      // ...
    }]
  }
  ```

- `node.preOrderIterator(until)`
Description: An iterator that yields every node at the subtree rooted at `node`.
Nodes are yielded before their children.  If the optional matcher `until` is
passed, subtrees for which `until` returns something truthy will not be yielded.

Example:

  ```js
  // for a tree
  //  TreeMerger
  //    |- Babel_1
  //    |- Babel_2
  //    |--|- Funnel
  for (n of node.preOrderIterator()) {
    console.log(n.label.name);
  }
  // prints
  //
  // TreeMerger
  // Babel_1
  // Babel_2
  // Funnel

  for (n of node.preOrderIterator(x => x.label.name === 'Babel_2')) {
    console.log(n.label.name);
  }
  // prints
  //
  //  TreeMerger
  //  |- Babel_1
  ```

- `node.postOrderIterator(until)`
Description:  An iterator that yields every node at the subtree rooted at
`node`.  Nodes are yielded after their children.  If the optional matcher
`until` is passed, subtrees for which `until` returns something truthy will not
be yielded.

Example:
  ```js
  // for a tree
  //  TreeMerger
  //    |- Babel_1
  //    |- Babel_2
  //    |--|- Funnel
  for (n of node.postOrderIterator()) {
    console.log(n.label.name);
  }
  // prints
  //
  // Funnel
  // Babel_2
  // Babel_1
  // TreeMerger
  ```

- `node.ancestorsIterator`
Description:  An iterator that yields every ancestor node of `node`, in order
from `node` to the root node.  `node` itself is not yielded.

Example:

  ```js
  // for a tree
  //  TreeMerger
  //    |- Babel_1
  //    |- Babel_2
  //    |--|- Funnel
  //
  // on node Funnel
  for (n of node.ancestorsIterator()) {
    console.log(n.label.name);
  }
  // prints
  //
  // Babel_2
  // TreeMerger
  ```

- `node.statsIterator`
Description: An iterator that yields pairs of stat names and values.
Example:

  ```js
  //  for a typical broccoli node
  for ([statName, statValue] of node.statsIterator()) {
    console.log(statName, statValue);
  }
  // prints
  //
  // "time.self" 64232794
  // "fs.statSync.count" 40
  // "fs.statSync.time" 401232123
  // ...
  ```

